'''Sir Louis Francis Loder''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|CBE}} (30 December 1896{{spaced endash}}11 February 1972) was a senior Australian public servant and policymaker. He was head of the Department of Works between 1945 and his retirement in 1961.

==Life and career==
Louis Loder was born in Sale, Victoria on 30 December 1896.<ref name=Lawrence>{{citation|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/loder-sir-louis-francis-10849|title=Loder, Sir Louis Francis (1896–1972)|first=T.F.C.|last=Lawrence|archivedate=22 December 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222121927/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/loder-sir-louis-francis-10849|publisher=Australian National University|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography}}</ref>

Loder served in the Australian Imperial Force during the First World War.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/people/rolls/R2044012/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427105035/https://www.awm.gov.au/people/rolls/R2044012/|archivedate=27 April 2014|title=First World War Embarkation Rolls - Louis Francis Loder|publisher=Australian War Memorial}}</ref>

Between 1928 and 1940, Loder was Chief Engineer at the Victorian Country Roads Board.<ref name=Retire>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article105855722|title=First Director|page=14|newspaper=The Canberra Times|date=13 December 1961}}</ref> He then went on to work for Allied Works between 1940 and 1945.<ref name=Retire/>

In 1945, Loder was appointed to be Director-General of the newly established [[Department of Works (1945)|Department of Works]] (later [[Department of Works and Housing]] and then [[Department of Works (1952–1973)|Department of Works (II)]]).<ref name="NAA CA 50">{{citation|title=CA 50: Department of Works [II], Central Office|url=http://naa12.naa.gov.au/scripts/SearchOld.asp?Number=CA+50|publisher=National Archives of Australia|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref><ref name="NAA CA 52">{{citation|title=CA 52: Department of Works and Housing, Head Office|url=http://naa12.naa.gov.au/scripts/SearchOld.asp?Number=CA+52|publisher=National Archives of Australia|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref><ref name="NAA CA 61">{{citation|title=CA 61: Department of Works [III], Central Office|url=http://naa12.naa.gov.au/scripts/SearchOld.asp?Number=CA+61|publisher=National Archives of Australia|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> In these roles, Loder was responsible for the design, costing, supervision and execution of all architectural and engineering works for the Australian Government.<ref name=Lawrence/> During this time he was occupied with work that included coordinating the works of experts to establish the Snowy River Hydro-electric scheme as urgent politics, working to manage the expansion of war aircraft facilities at Mascot Airport in Sydney and managing the rocket range at Woomera.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article63306784|title=Mr. Louis Loder: Man from Snowy River|date=12 May 1949|page=7|newspaper=Gippsland Times}}</ref>

Loder retired from the [[Australian Public Service]] in 1961.<ref name=Lawrence/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article105896754|title=New Works Chief Appointed|date=14 October 1961|page=12|newspaper=The Canberra Times}}</ref> On retirement, Loder was planning a 13-month overseas holiday.<ref name=Retire/>

Loder died in Healesville, Victoria on 11 February 1972.<ref name=Lawrence/>

==Awards and honours==
Loder was made a Commander of the Order of the British Empire in June&nbsp;1953.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1065287&search_type=quick&showInd=true|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427103041/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1065287&search_type=quick&showInd=true|archivedate=27 April 2014|title=Search Australian Honours: LODER, Louis Francis|publisher=Australian Government|work=itsanhonour.gov.au}}</ref> He was appointed a Knight Bachelor in June&nbsp;1962.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1082882&search_type=quick&showInd=true|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427103151/http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1082882&search_type=quick&showInd=true|archivedate=27 April 2014|title=Search Australian Honours: LODER, Louis Francis|publisher=Australian Government|work=itsanhonour.gov.au}}</ref>

In 1987, a street in the [[Canberra]] suburb of [[Theodore, Australian Capital Territory|Theodore]] was named Louis Loder Street in Loder's honour.<ref name=Theodore>{{citation|url=http://www.actpla.act.gov.au/tools_resources/place_search3?sq_content_src=%2BdXJsPWh0dHAlM0ElMkYlMkYyMDMuOS4yNDkuMyUyRlBsYWNlTmFtZXMlMkZQbGFjZURldGFpbHMuYXNweCUzRm9iamVjdElEJTNEODU1MSZhbGw9MQ%3D%3D |title=Louis Loder Street |publisher=ACT Government Environment and Sustainable Development Directorate |archivedate=28 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140428092546/http://www.actpla.act.gov.au/tools_resources/place_search3?sq_content_src=%2BdXJsPWh0dHAlM0ElMkYlMkYyMDMuOS4yNDkuMyUyRlBsYWNlTmFtZXMlMkZQbGFjZURldGFpbHMuYXNweCUzRm9iamVjdElEJTNEODU1MSZhbGw9MQ%3D%3D |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>

